Demonstration of gitwords

Taylor Spears

23 February 2015

require("gitwords")
## Loading required package: gitwords
## Loading required package: ggplot2

The three functions can be called with a single date or a range of dates as inputs. When get_words is called with a single date, it reports the word counts for that particular date. When word_stats and plot_words are called with a single date, they calculate summary statistics and build plots using all commits since that date:

get_words(date="2013-12-01",
          repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
##         Date Net Additions Net Modifications
## 1 2013-12-01           142               434
word_stats(date="2013-07-01",
           repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## $`Summary Statistics`
##        Net Additions Net Modifications
## Mean        1424.080          6032.253
## Median      1203.500          4317.000
## StDev       1444.368          5478.794
## Min        -1958.000             8.000
## Max         9825.000         27640.000
## 
## $`Weekly Statistics`
##                            Monday Tuesday Wednesday Thursday Friday
## Net Additions (median)     1129.0    1265      1337     1277   1322
## Net Modifications (median) 4962.5    3283      4348     4065   4548
##                            Saturday Sunday
## Net Additions (median)       1203.5    919
## Net Modifications (median)   4530.5   3980
plot_words(date="2013-07-01",
           repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## Loading required package: grid

You can also supply a range of dates to the functions, in which case all commits between those two dates are used:

get_words(date=c("2013-12-01","2013-12-07"),
          repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
##         Date Net Additions Net Modifications
## 1 2013-12-01           142               434
## 2 2013-12-02          1088             14164
## 3 2013-12-03          1140              2494
## 4 2013-12-04          1949              3747
## 5 2013-12-05          2866              5874
## 6 2013-12-06          1235             12931
## 7 2013-12-07          -164              4526
word_stats(date=c("2013-07-01","2013-12-07"),
          repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## $`Summary Statistics`
##        Net Additions Net Modifications
## Mean        1606.774          6083.642
## Median      1271.000          4311.500
## StDev       1500.951          5691.941
## Min         -490.000             8.000
## Max         9825.000         27640.000
## 
## $`Weekly Statistics`
##                            Monday Tuesday Wednesday Thursday Friday
## Net Additions (median)     1351.5    1265      1523   1250.0   1550

##                            Saturday Sunday
## Net Additions (median)       1185.5    944
## Net Modifications (median)   3801.0   3616
plot_words(date=c("2013-01-01","2014-02-17"),

Finally, you can omit providing the date altogether. Omitting the date parameter has different effects for the three functions. get_words will report word counts for todays date if no date is supplied.

get_words(repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## Error in subset_commits_date(a, date): No commits on 2015-02-24

which throws an error, since I have no commited any writing to my thesis repository today.

By comparison, word_stats and plot_words will use all commits in the repository if no date parameter is supplied:

word_stats(repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## $`Summary Statistics`
##        Net Additions Net Modifications
## Mean        1263.820          5051.966
## Median      1013.000          3447.500
## StDev       1359.623          5137.483
## Min        -1958.000             8.000
## Max         9825.000         27640.000
## 
## $`Weekly Statistics`
##                            Monday Tuesday Wednesday Thursday Friday
## Net Additions (median)     1024.5   765.0    1080.5     1168   1164
## Net Modifications (median) 3136.0  2516.5    3639.5     3006   3517
##                            Saturday Sunday
## Net Additions (median)       1185.5    854
## Net Modifications (median)   4335.0   3176
plot_words(repo="~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.
## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is <1000, so using loess. Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Finally, if you omit the repo parameter, then the functions will use your current working directory as the git repository. For example,

setwd("~/Dropbox/Repositories/Thesis")
get_words(date="2013-12-01")
##         Date Net Additions Net Modifications
## 1 2013-12-01           142               434
